  "texts": [
    "I. INTRODUCTIONL ARGE Language Models (LLMs) have significantly ad- vanced in recent years, driving progress in natural language processing and artificial intelligence [1], [2].",
    "Despite their prowess, these models often encounter errors that can deteriorate the quality of their output, affecting their practical usability and user trust [3].",
    "The complexity of these models, coupled with the expansive scope of their training data, predisposes them to occasional inaccuracies and biases [4], [5].",
    "This is particularly problematic when these models are deployed in language-specific contexts, such as with the Chinese Large Language Model, Kimi.",
    "For models like Kimi, robust error correction mechanisms are not just beneficial but necessary to maintain reliability and user trust."
  ],
